      "testId": 1,
      "type": "multiple-choice",
      "passage": "THE INDUSTRIAL REVOLUTION\n\nThe Industrial Revolution, which began in Britain in the mid-18th century, fundamentally transformed how goods were produced and how people lived. Before this period, most manufacturing was done by hand, often in people's homes or small workshops — a system known as cottage industry. The introduction of machinery powered by steam engines and later electricity dramatically increased production capacity.\n\nFactories emerged as the new centres of production, drawing workers from rural areas into rapidly growing urban centres. Cities such as Manchester, Birmingham, and Leeds expanded at extraordinary rates, often without adequate housing, sanitation, or infrastructure to support the influx of population.\n\nWhile the revolution brought unprecedented economic growth and new consumer goods, it also created new social problems: difficult working conditions, child labour, and overcrowded, polluted cities became widespread concerns. Social reformers and early trade unions eventually pushed for legislation to address these problems, laying the groundwork for modern labour laws and social welfare systems.\n\nThe revolution also had global consequences, enabling Britain to build a vast industrial empire and reshaping trade relationships across continents. The technologies and economic models it generated influenced industrialisation processes in Europe, the United States, and later Asia throughout the 19th and 20th centuries.",
